# LLM Router — Cursor Rules
# Place this file at: .cursor/rules/llm-router.mdc
# It tells Cursor's agent when to automatically invoke each MCP tool.

## Auto-routing rules

When the user asks about architecture, system design, project structure, or
"how should I build X", ALWAYS use the `plan_workflow` MCP tool first.

When the user asks to write complex logic, algorithms, refactor code, debug
something tricky, or review/explain code, use `generate_code`.

When the user asks to implement a feature, add an endpoint, write tests,
or do repetitive coding tasks, use `implement_feature`.

When the task is ambiguous, use `route_prompt` and let the router decide.

After completing a task with one tool, you MAY chain to another:
  e.g. plan_workflow → generate_code → implement_feature

Use `clear_context` when the user starts a completely new, unrelated task.

## Session IDs
Use a consistent session_id per conversation to preserve context.
A good default: use the current file name or feature name as session_id.
Example: session_id="auth-module" or session_id="checkout-flow"

## Token-saving reminders
- Do NOT repeat large code blocks back to the user when confirming.
- Summarise what was generated, then show only the changed sections.
